data_item.opening_hours: Monday to Saturday, 10:00 AM to 7:30 PM
data_item.description:
Saint-Tropez, 1971, a terrace caf where a young man is sketching an original design for swim shorts on a checked tablecloth. Inspired by surfers trunks, the design takes shape, very different from the traditional swim briefs of the time. Colorful and original, a new style is set!

Made out of spinnaker canvas (sailing is, after all, the king of sports in the gulf of Saint-Tropez), the new swimsuit dries more quickly in the sun and wind. Close-up of the first Vilebrequin, the French word for crankshaft and a reference to its designers passion for automobiles.

On the beaches of Saint-Tropez, the new swim trunks are an overnight success. Practical and comfortable, colourful and trs chic, a trend is launched, a new brand is born.

data_item.name: Sara Melki
data_item.address: Ground Floor, Marc 1 Building, Habtoor Roundabout, Horch Tabet
data_item.description:
Sara Melki a young Lebanese designer, learned to draw and sew during her internship at Maison Rabih Kayrouz, then went to perfect her skills at Paris prestigious Studio Berot, where she mingled with aspiring designers from the four corners of the world. During a six-month internship at Mahlia Kent, a company that creates weaves for the most important fashion houses in the world, one of the patterns she made was chosen by Chanel.

Melki then moved to New York to work at Proenza Schouler where really learned the importance of business in fashion.

Melki, who is 26, is now at the helm of her own company and of the Espace M concept store (in Sin El Fil). She sells her one-of-a-kind collection, where she contrasts rich textiles brocade, lace, tweed, polished cotton and sharp cuts (mini shorts are a favorite) for a sexy urban style.

Melki loves textiles. Thick tweeds, patterned leather, ethereal silks, vivid tints. She still gets fabric from Mahlia Kent and tailors dresses and outfits for special orders, She has also developed line for accessories. Just dont expect a red-carper-style gown for your wedding: the designer is more likely to dress you in an architectural top and tiny shorts.

GEOX is the premier Italian footwear brand for men and women known for its invention of the "shoe that breathes".
The brand was set up in 1995 and consolidated its position in the Italian market up to 2000. From 2000 to 2003, it expanded it sales at international level, using exclusive and multi brand channels and has created a cult-like following in more than 100 countries with its breathable technology and stylish Italian design.
In recent years, the group's growth has been supported by massive investments in its own outlets. Its success was certainly due to the technology of the show that breathes but also to the Italian know -how, style and design that Geox adds to its collection and the quality of the skins produced in Italy. Thanks to this mix Geox can produce quality products with a fashion and comfort content, positioning its products at medium / medium - high price level accessible for the customer.
Geox mission is to diffuse innovation, especially when it comes to creating technological solutions that ensure breathability and impermeability.

data_item.name: Milia M
data_item.address: Saifi Village Des Arts, 1051 Bloc D
data_item.opening_hours: Monday to Saturday, 11:00 AM to 7:00 PM
data_item.description:
Milia M was born and brought up in Beirut but chose Paris to study fashion design. After having worked as lingerie designer, she returned to Beirut to set up her own studio where she launched her first collection in 1999. Since then, Milia M has been producing two collections a year and sells all over the world.

Balanced between sobriety and joy, Milia's collections perfectly encapsulate the designer's spirit. Her clothing is exuberant, romantic and modern, with just a hint of Middle Eastern mystery. Softly feminine, Milia M's designs are essays in subtle seduction. They wrap the body in an interplay of transparencies, folds and openings that sensuously suggest more than they actually reveal.

Adept at the art of the body-hugging cut, milia m invites attention through her deft use of imaginative details, which simultaneously heighten anticipation and subvert expectations of familiarity.

data_item.description: From High Street to High End, Label Queen's concept gathers together various brands and creators from various directions, creating a beautiful fashionable chaos. data_item.name: Kamishibai

data_item.description: At the heart of Beiruts elegant Achrafieh district is Kamishibai, a multi-brand boutique which offers its faithful clients exclusive international fashion labels, spread along two spacious floors.  Among the Men's and Ladies' lines, one can find a mixture of refined Italian, French and British brands that inspire comfort and well-being. Breaking from traditional boundaries since 1985, Kamishibai introduces its customers to worldwide distinct apparel, hip-designed spaces, online presence and meticulous customer care.

Taten inspires those who enter it to discover themselves, leaving refreshed, regenerated and looking highly fashionable.

data_item.opening_hours: Monday to Saturday, 9:00 AM to 5:00 PM
data_item.description:
Embellish, drape and clutch even the neglected parts of your body with Cera Barr body jewelry.

As a singer and former drama teacher driven by performance art, Sara Barraj focused her talent to costume design and began making bold body pieces to wear on stage. The collection grew to a dynamic range of imperial-chic and modern-ethnic designs by merging organic structure and functionality with valuable metals, crystals, and textiles. Fashion accessories from Cera Barr are a must have if you want to wear the latest trend.

Looking to get a custom made piece for yourself? Get your personalized body jewelry by Cera Barr.

In the light of its influences, the house of Sandra Mansour is generally drawn towards evening wear and wedding dresses. The cocktail dress takes pride of place, combining subtle European elegance with the bold and audacious style of the contemporary Middle East.

data_item.name: Lara Khoury
data_item.address: 2nd Floor, 406 Gouraud Street
data_item.opening_hours: Monday to Friday, 10:00 AM to 6:00 PM
data_item.description:
Lara Khoury graduated from the Ecole Suprieure de la Mode de Paris (ESMOD) in 2006, before joining Elie Saab in Beirut in 2006 where she discovered the world of Haute Couture, Prt--porter, fashion and all the dynamics of the industry. A year later, her very first pieces were put forth to the general public in Starch (Saifi Village), Rabih Kayrouz and Tala Hajjar's laboratory for new ideas and a showroom for young Lebanese designers.  In 2010, the enthusiasm of the press and the audience was heightened, and the artist found the self-confidence to launch her first eponymous collection; Lara Khoury becomes Lara Khoury and settles in the center of Beirut, in a showroom/workshop on Gouraud street.

Today, the fashion designer has found herself a space, intimate and personal, crucial and essential to obtain certain plenitude, a different creation, with the wish to transmit and share what we call, sensitivity and emotion.  Lara Khourys style is sincere, bold, moving and minimalist. It involves a young and experimental trend, continuously concerned with detail, and carrying a passion for innovation and freedom.  On May 2011, Lara was selected to represent Lebanon in the second generation of the Maison Mditerranenne des Mtiers de la Mode in Marseille (France). A Master Class between Marseille and Paris with renowned icons of the international fashion scene (including Dior and Chanel), as well as others from the creative and economic identity of Marseille.

data_item.description: Born and raised in Paris till the age of 18 years old, Nadine Mneimneh returned to Beirut in 2001 to pursue a BA in business administration at the American University of Beirut. Her interest for fashion was revealed after attending a styling course at Istituto Marangoni Milan in 2004, after which she carried on with 6 years of experience in the industry. With another bachelors degree in fashion design and pattern-making from ESMOD Beirut, Nadine launched her own ready-to-wear label in 2010 with the help of the Starch foundation, a project aimed at showcasing up-and-coming Lebanese designers.  Nadines style is defined by a loose and minimal silhouette hinting femininity, comfortable and modern fits along an artisanal touch, and lines and volumes sharpened by the use of refined menswear fabrics.
